<figure class=3D"mw-default-size" typeof=3D"mw:File/Thumb"><a href=3D"https=
://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/File:Video_game_loot_box_mockup.png" class=3D"mw-f=
ile-description"><img src=3D"https://upload.wikimedia.org/wikipedia/commons=
/thumb/0/0e/Video_game_loot_box_mockup.png/250px-Video_game_loot_box_mockup=
.png" decoding=3D"async" width=3D"250" height=3D"188" class=3D"mw-file-elem=
ent" data-file-width=3D"1024" data-file-height=3D"768"></a><figcaption>Gach=
a mechanics have been compared to those of <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.=
org/wiki/Loot_box" title=3D"Loot box">loot boxes</a>.</figcaption></figure>
<p>A <b><span title=3D"Japanese-language text"><i lang=3D"ja-Latn">gacha</i=
></span> game</b><span style=3D"font-weight: normal"> (<a href=3D"https://e=
n.wikipedia.org/wiki/Japanese_language" title=3D"Japanese language">Japanes=
e</a>: <span lang=3D"ja">=E3=82=AC=E3=83=81=E3=83=A3=E3=82=B2=E3=83=BC=E3=
=83=A0</span>, <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Hepburn_romanizatio=
n" title=3D"Hepburn romanization">Hepburn</a>: <span title=3D"Hepburn trans=
literation"><i lang=3D"ja-Latn">gacha g=C4=93mu</i></span>)</span> is a gam=
e, typically a <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Video_game" title=
=3D"Video game">video game</a>, that implements the <span title=3D"Japanese=
-language text"><i lang=3D"ja-Latn"><a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wik=
i/Gashapon" title=3D"Gashapon">gachapon</a></i></span> machine style mechan=
ics. Similar to <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Loot_boxes" class=
=3D"mw-redirect" title=3D"Loot boxes">loot boxes</a>, <a href=3D"https://en=
.wikipedia.org/wiki/Games_as_a_service" class=3D"mw-redirect" title=3D"Game=
s as a service">live service</a> gacha games entice players to spend <a hre=
f=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Virtual_economy" title=3D"Virtual econom=
y">in-game currency</a> to receive a random in-game item. Some in-game curr=
ency can be gained through game play and staying up-to-date, and some by pu=
rchasing it from the game publisher using real-world funds.
</p><p>Most common gacha games are <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki=
/Free-to-play" title=3D"Free-to-play">free-to-play</a> (F2P) <a href=3D"htt=
ps://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Mobile_games" class=3D"mw-redirect" title=3D"Mob=
ile games">mobile</a> <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Role-playing=
_video_game" title=3D"Role-playing video game">role-playing video games</a>=
 with an emphasis on strategy, such as team building, synergizing and playe=
r improvisation.<sup id=3D"cite_ref-:1_1-0" class=3D"reference"><a href=3D"=
https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Gacha_game#cite_note-:1-1"><span class=3D"cit=
e-bracket">[</span>1<span class=3D"cite-bracket">]</span></a></sup><sup id=
=3D"cite_ref-:0_2-0" class=3D"reference"><a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.or=
g/wiki/Gacha_game#cite_note-:0-2"><span class=3D"cite-bracket">[</span>2<sp=
an class=3D"cite-bracket">]</span></a></sup>
</p><p>The <span title=3D"Japanese-language text"><i lang=3D"ja-Latn">gacha=
</i></span> game model has been around since the early 90s with strategy <a=
 href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Collectible_card_game" title=3D"Coll=
ectible card game">trading card games</a> such as <a href=3D"https://en.wik=
ipedia.org/wiki/Magic:_The_Gathering" title=3D"Magic: The Gathering"><i>Mag=
ic: the Gathering</i></a>, but began to be widely used in the early 2010s i=
n mobile gaming by <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Video_games_in_=
Japan" title=3D"Video games in Japan">Japan</a>.<sup id=3D"cite_ref-:1_1-1"=
 class=3D"reference"><a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Gacha_game#ci=
te_note-:1-1"><span class=3D"cite-bracket">[</span>1<span class=3D"cite-bra=
cket">]</span></a></sup><sup id=3D"cite_ref-:0_2-1" class=3D"reference"><a =
href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Gacha_game#cite_note-:0-2"><span clas=
s=3D"cite-bracket">[</span>2<span class=3D"cite-bracket">]</span></a></sup>=
 Gacha mechanics have become an integral part of Japanese mobile game cultu=
re as well as pop culture in general.<sup id=3D"cite_ref-GFy_3-0" class=3D"=
reference"><a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Gacha_game#cite_note-GF=
y-3"><span class=3D"cite-bracket">[</span>3<span class=3D"cite-bracket">]</=
span></a></sup> The game mechanism is also increasingly used in <a href=3D"=
https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Video_games_in_China" title=3D"Video games in=
 China">Chinese</a> and <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Video_game=
s_in_South_Korea" title=3D"Video games in South Korea">Korean</a> games, as=
 well as European and American games.<sup id=3D"cite_ref-GFy_3-1" class=3D"=
reference"><a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Gacha_game#cite_note-GF=
y-3"><span class=3D"cite-bracket">[</span>3<span class=3D"cite-bracket">]</=
span></a></sup><sup id=3D"cite_ref-4" class=3D"reference"><a href=3D"https:=
//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Gacha_game#cite_note-4"><span class=3D"cite-bracket=
">[</span>4<span class=3D"cite-bracket">]</span></a></sup><sup id=3D"cite_r=
ef-JPT_5-0" class=3D"reference"><a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Ga=
cha_game#cite_note-JPT-5"><span class=3D"cite-bracket">[</span>5<span class=
=3D"cite-bracket">]</span></a></sup><sup id=3D"cite_ref-johannesheinze_6-0"=
 class=3D"reference"><a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Gacha_game#ci=
te_note-johannesheinze-6"><span class=3D"cite-bracket">[</span>6<span class=
=3D"cite-bracket">]</span></a></sup>
</p><p>Digital <i>gacha</i> games have been criticized for being designed t=
o be addictive in order to attract <i><a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/w=
iki/Whale_(gambling)" class=3D"mw-redirect" title=3D"Whale (gambling)">whal=
es</a></i> to spend money on <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Micro=
transactions" class=3D"mw-redirect" title=3D"Microtransactions">microtransa=
ctions</a> far beyond the usual price of a video game. The typical gacha ga=
me format that encourages spending real-world money on <a href=3D"https://e=
n.wikipedia.org/wiki/Probability" title=3D"Probability">chance</a>-based lo=
ot tables with in-game rewards of differing value instead of individual spe=
cific purchases has been compared to <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wi=
ki/Gambling" title=3D"Gambling">gambling</a>.<sup id=3D"cite_ref-7" class=
=3D"reference"><a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Gacha_game#cite_not=
e-7"><span class=3D"cite-bracket">[</span>7<span class=3D"cite-bracket">]</=
span></a></sup>
</p>
<meta property=3D"mw:PageProp/toc">
<div class=3D"mw-heading mw-heading2"><h2 id=3D"Gameplay">Gameplay</h2><spa=
n class=3D"mw-editsection"><span class=3D"mw-editsection-bracket">[</span><=
a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/w/index.php?title=3DGacha_game&amp;actio=
n=3Dedit&amp;section=3D1" title=3D"Edit section: Gameplay"><span>edit</span=
></a><span class=3D"mw-editsection-bracket">]</span></span></div>
<p>Due to the randomized nature of gacha games, many original gachas are of=
ten strategy games or feature elements of strong strategy considerations, e=
ncouraging the player to improvise their own solution to problems while als=
o being attentive about new additions to the roster of obtainable character=
s/items that can add more flexibility to a player's strategy in late/post-g=
ame modes such as boss raids and tower-styled challenge rooms.
</p><p>In many older games, <span title=3D"Japanese-language text"><i lang=
=3D"ja-Latn">gacha</i></span> rewards are essential for players to make pro=
gress in the game, although certain newer gacha games allow for more flexib=
ility on progression through core content.<sup id=3D"cite_ref-johannesheinz=
e_6-1" class=3D"reference"><a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Gacha_g=
ame#cite_note-johannesheinze-6"><span class=3D"cite-bracket">[</span>6<span=
 class=3D"cite-bracket">]</span></a></sup> While players can earn the "prem=
ium" currency during gameplay, it is available in controlled amounts at the=
 developer's discretion, with holidays and special events usually boosting =
the amounts given.
</p><p>Banners are "pools" of available items (characters, loot, cards, etc=
) that players can "roll" on. Offered banners can be perpetually available =
or can have a limited duration. Games generally have some of both, with pla=
yer retention efforts and in-game advertising in some games emphasizing the=
 <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/FOMO" class=3D"mw-redirect" title=
=3D"FOMO">limited availability</a> of some or all of the items in the latte=
r. Many kinds of virtual items can be in the loot table for a <a href=3D"ht=
tps://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Gacha_game#Banners">banner</a>. Gameplay units =
such as cards, characters, equippable gear, or more abstract loot such as "=
experience" are all possible. Sometimes, these banners are limited, such th=
at specific prizes can only be obtained within a specific event time-frame.=
<sup id=3D"cite_ref-GFy_3-2" class=3D"reference"><a href=3D"https://en.wiki=
pedia.org/wiki/Gacha_game#cite_note-GFy-3"><span class=3D"cite-bracket">[</=
span>3<span class=3D"cite-bracket">]</span></a></sup> Sometimes, games lift=
 the limited status of certain items to be "commons" or even free, but this=
 is not seen often.
</p><p>Stamina is a resource that is required for, and consumed by, core in=
-game actions such as engaging with the game, like beginning combat encount=
ers in a fighting-oriented game. It regenerates over time, often only up to=
 a cap. It can typically be regenerated or gained instantly through some fo=
rm of currency spending, either premium <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org=
/wiki/Microtransaction" title=3D"Microtransaction">microtransaction</a> or =
earned in game. The name for this resource is usually different on a per-ga=
me basis, but stamina is typically the general term used for this type of c=
urrency in general across games. Stamina is not always treated as the basis=
 of progression, sometimes only being required for side content. Other time=
s, Stamina burnt is often translated into experience points for an player's=
 entire account in more quick, casual oriented games. In more competitive g=
ames such as online trading card games or non-live service RPG games such a=
s <i><a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Xenoblade_Chronicles_2" title=
=3D"Xenoblade Chronicles 2">Xenoblade 2</a></i>, they are generally not use=
d for play. =20
</p><p>Some gacha games often feature several in-game currencies with intri=
cate conversion methods, obscuring the actual value of non-premium currenci=
es. In some games, players are generally given free or discounted <span tit=
le=3D"Japanese-language text"><i lang=3D"ja-Latn">gachas</i></span> in low =
amounts on a regular schedule, in exchange for logging in or doing in-game =
tasks.
</p><p>Because of the nature of the player-developer relationship, the free=
 to play experience is often a case-by-case basis dependant on a developer'=
s attitude towards the development of their game and their player base as w=
ell as how well they implement luck mitigation mechanics such as sparking s=
ystems that allow the player to obtain the item within a limit, which are a=
lso case-by-case implementations of reliability and frequency, assuming the=
y are implemented at all.
</p>
<div class=3D"mw-heading mw-heading2"><h2 id=3D"Model">Model</h2><span clas=
s=3D"mw-editsection"><span class=3D"mw-editsection-bracket">[</span><a href=
=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/w/index.php?title=3DGacha_game&amp;action=3Ded=
it&amp;section=3D2" title=3D"Edit section: Model"><span>edit</span></a><spa=
n class=3D"mw-editsection-bracket">]</span></span></div>
<figure class=3D"mw-default-size" typeof=3D"mw:File/Thumb"><a href=3D"https=
://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/File:%E3%82%AC%E3%82%B7%E3%83%A3%E3%83%9D%E3%83%B3=
_(14396462196).jpg" class=3D"mw-file-description"><img src=3D"https://uploa=
d.wikimedia.org/wikipedia/commons/thumb/e/e7/%E3%82%AC%E3%82%B7%E3%83%A3%E3=
%83%9D%E3%83%B3_%2814396462196%29.jpg/250px-%E3%82%AC%E3%82%B7%E3%83%A3%E3%=
83%9D%E3%83%B3_%2814396462196%29.jpg" decoding=3D"async" width=3D"250" heig=
ht=3D"167" class=3D"mw-file-element" data-file-width=3D"4896" data-file-hei=
ght=3D"3264"></a><figcaption>The games are named after <i>gachapon</i> <a h=
ref=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Vending_machine" title=3D"Vending mach=
ine">vending machines</a>, which dispense capsules containing randomly-sele=
cted toys</figcaption></figure>
<p>A marketing practice where deals of a product are shown to the consumer =
so they perceive what they are buying as a good deal. This is used in gacha=
 as extra roll deals and virtual currency deals to get the consumer to buy =
more. Studies show that consumers buy on the basis of the price of a single=
 product and not all of the products prices combined which entrepreneurs ta=
ke advantage of. Customers only look at the price at hand of a product and =
compare that to the deal and not the sub charges of the product. In mobile =
games this is used by a cheap product to set the anchor then the more expen=
sive ones that shows deals making the player feel better for a purchase bec=
ause they have more value.<sup id=3D"cite_ref-:3_8-0" class=3D"reference"><=
a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Gacha_game#cite_note-:3-8"><span cl=
ass=3D"cite-bracket">[</span>8<span class=3D"cite-bracket">]</span></a></su=
p>
</p><p>To further immerse players, they are rewarded gifts at random interv=
als throughout the game. This encourages players to either play or else pay=
 to get valuable items. An example of this is getting a free gacha pull by =
doing certain tasks in the game.<sup id=3D"cite_ref-:3_8-1" class=3D"refere=
nce"><a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Gacha_game#cite_note-:3-8"><s=
pan class=3D"cite-bracket">[</span>8<span class=3D"cite-bracket">]</span></=
a></sup>
</p><p>Gacha games often use a 'near miss' technique inspired by gambling, =
in which the player's pull briefly shows a valuable or rare item before sto=
pping on a different, less desirable one. This gives the player the impress=
ion of being close to obtaining their desired item, and that a subsequent p=
ull will result in success. By passing over other potential rewards before =
stopping on the one the player receives, the game gives the player <a href=
=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Fear_of_missing_out" title=3D"Fear of mis=
sing out">a sense of having missed out</a>, and encourages them to spend mo=
re to obtain rare items.<sup id=3D"cite_ref-:3_8-2" class=3D"reference"><a =
href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Gacha_game#cite_note-:3-8"><span clas=
s=3D"cite-bracket">[</span>8<span class=3D"cite-bracket">]</span></a></sup>
</p><p>Some items are only available for a limited amount of time, incentiv=
izing players to directly purchase or otherwise obtain the item for an in-g=
ame power advantage or bragging rights. Limited time events can also condit=
ion players to consistently play the game out of fear missing an event or s=
pecific item. Daily login rewards can encourage players to open the game ea=
ch day in order to collect a specific daily reward.<sup id=3D"cite_ref-9" c=
lass=3D"reference"><a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Gacha_game#cite=
_note-9"><span class=3D"cite-bracket">[</span>9<span class=3D"cite-bracket"=
>]</span></a></sup>
</p><p>A gacha game will have collectable characters, cards, or other items=
. Many of them are obtainable only through a "gacha" mechanic,<sup id=3D"ci=
te_ref-GFy_3-3" class=3D"reference"><a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wik=
i/Gacha_game#cite_note-GFy-3"><span class=3D"cite-bracket">[</span>3<span c=
lass=3D"cite-bracket">]</span></a></sup> wherein the player exchanges in-ga=
me currency for "pulls" or "spins", each pull yielding a random collectable=
 "drop".=20
</p><p>Some of the "drops" drop less frequently than others. As such, drops=
 can often be categorized into rarity "tiers". Historically, gacha games di=
d not always share their drop rates. Those that did so were called "open ga=
cha" and those that did not were "closed gacha". In many jurisdictions it i=
s now legally required for the item rarities to be public information. As s=
uch, virtually all contemporary gacha games share this information.
</p><p>Between rarity and limited-time availability drops, players are ince=
ntivized to <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Fear_of_missing_out" t=
itle=3D"Fear of missing out">roll while their desired item is available</a>=
.<sup id=3D"cite_ref-GFy_3-4" class=3D"reference"><a href=3D"https://en.wik=
ipedia.org/wiki/Gacha_game#cite_note-GFy-3"><span class=3D"cite-bracket">[<=
/span>3<span class=3D"cite-bracket">]</span></a></sup>
</p><p>Some gacha games use a luck mitigation model using "inevitable guara=
nteed drop" mechanic dubbed by players as a "pity" or "spark": the player w=
ill be guaranteed a given drop after pulling for it a large number of times=
 without success. This mechanic by itself does not start at the beginning b=
ut rather at a fixed point. Pity mechanics can be "soft" or "hard". Dependi=
ng on the game, these mechanics usually start at a designated pull count an=
d at the very end for that matter. <sup class=3D"noprint Inline-Template" s=
tyle=3D"margin-left:0.1em; white-space:nowrap;">[<i><a href=3D"https://en.w=
ikipedia.org/wiki/Wikipedia:Please_clarify" title=3D"Wikipedia:Please clari=
fy"><span title=3D"The text near this tag may need clarification or removal=
 of jargon. (September 2024)">clarification needed</span></a></i>]</sup> "S=
oft" pity increases the probability slightly of getting a rare item with ev=
ery pull, counting up and recalculating the probability until the rare item=
 is received, while "hard" pity uses a counter or "fail currency" to keep t=
rack of the number of pulls and automatically dispense or allow the item to=
 be purchasable with said in-game currency after reaching a preset number o=
f rolls. Due to the nature of Hard pity, it is often a recommended strategy=
 by players to never roll for a character or item unless they are capable o=
f making it to the 100% guarantee by saving enough currency to reach the sp=
ark limit, essentially "buying" the character. <sup class=3D"noprint Inline=
-Template Template-Fact" style=3D"white-space:nowrap;">[<i><a href=3D"https=
://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Wikipedia:Citation_needed" title=3D"Wikipedia:Cita=
tion needed"><span title=3D"This claim needs references to reliable sources=
. (June 2024)">citation needed</span></a></i>]</sup>
</p>
<div class=3D"mw-heading mw-heading2"><h2 id=3D"Variations">Variations</h2>=
<span class=3D"mw-editsection"><span class=3D"mw-editsection-bracket">[</sp=
an><a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/w/index.php?title=3DGacha_game&amp;a=
ction=3Dedit&amp;section=3D3" title=3D"Edit section: Variations"><span>edit=
</span></a><span class=3D"mw-editsection-bracket">]</span></span></div>
<p>This is a list of game mechanics that may be used in a game's implementa=
tion of gacha mechanics. Some mechanics are nearly or entirely obsolete due=
 to regulatory requirements.
</p>
<dl><dt>Complete <span title=3D"Japanese-language text"><i lang=3D"ja-Latn"=
>gacha</i></span></dt>
<dd>"Complete <i>gacha</i>"<span style=3D"font-weight: normal"> (<span titl=
e=3D"Japanese-language text"><span lang=3D"ja">=E3=82=B3=E3=83=B3=E3=83=97=
=E3=83=AA=E3=83=BC=E3=83=88=E3=82=AC=E3=83=81=E3=83=A3</span></span>)</span=
>, also shortened as "kompu gacha"<sup id=3D"cite_ref-10" class=3D"referenc=
e"><a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Gacha_game#cite_note-10"><span =
class=3D"cite-bracket">[</span>10<span class=3D"cite-bracket">]</span></a><=
/sup><sup id=3D"cite_ref-:7_11-0" class=3D"reference"><a href=3D"https://en=
.wikipedia.org/wiki/Gacha_game#cite_note-:7-11"><span class=3D"cite-bracket=
">[</span>11<span class=3D"cite-bracket">]</span></a></sup> or "compu gacha=
"<sup id=3D"cite_ref-siliconera_12-0" class=3D"reference"><a href=3D"https:=
//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Gacha_game#cite_note-siliconera-12"><span class=3D"=
cite-bracket">[</span>12<span class=3D"cite-bracket">]</span></a></sup> <sp=
an style=3D"font-weight: normal">(<span title=3D"Japanese-language text"><s=
pan lang=3D"ja">=E3=82=B3=E3=83=B3=E3=83=97=E3=82=AC=E3=83=81=E3=83=A3</spa=
n></span>)</span>, is a <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Monetizati=
on" title=3D"Monetization">monetization</a> model popular in Japanese mobil=
e <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Video_game" title=3D"Video game"=
>video games</a> until 2012, when it was made illegal by Japan's <a href=3D=
"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Consumer_Affairs_Agency" title=3D"Consumer A=
ffairs Agency">Consumer Affairs Agency</a>. In this scheme, there are desir=
able items that cannot be rolled for directly. The player must collect (tha=
t is, pull) a specific set of other items, and upon completion they unlock =
the desirable item. The first few items in a set can be rapidly acquired bu=
t as the number of missing items decreases it becomes increasingly unlikely=
 that redeeming a loot box will complete the set (see <a href=3D"https://en=
.wikipedia.org/wiki/Coupon_collector%27s_problem" title=3D"Coupon collector=
's problem">coupon collector's problem</a>) since eventually one single, sp=
ecific item is required.<sup id=3D"cite_ref-:7_11-1" class=3D"reference"><a=
 href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Gacha_game#cite_note-:7-11"><span cl=
ass=3D"cite-bracket">[</span>11<span class=3D"cite-bracket">]</span></a></s=
up></dd></dl>
<dl><dt>Box <span title=3D"Japanese-language text"><i lang=3D"ja-Latn">gach=
a</i></span></dt>
<dd>Box gacha is "pulling, without replacement". There is a slate of items =
in the box or banner, in specific quantities rather than via "with replacem=
ent", each-roll-is-independent probability. Over successive rolls, the set =
of possible "draws" shrinks until the player has all of the items.<sup id=
=3D"cite_ref-itsconferencepaper_13-0" class=3D"reference"><a href=3D"https:=
//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Gacha_game#cite_note-itsconferencepaper-13"><span c=
lass=3D"cite-bracket">[</span>13<span class=3D"cite-bracket">]</span></a></=
sup><sup id=3D"cite_ref-serkantoto_14-0" class=3D"reference"><a href=3D"htt=
ps://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Gacha_game#cite_note-serkantoto-14"><span class=
=3D"cite-bracket">[</span>14<span class=3D"cite-bracket">]</span></a></sup>=
</dd>
<dt>Redraw <span title=3D"Japanese-language text"><i lang=3D"ja-Latn">gacha=
</i></span></dt>
<dd>Redraw <span title=3D"Japanese-language text"><i lang=3D"ja-Latn">gacha=
</i></span> allows the player to "re-roll": to give up the rolled item in e=
xchange for another roll and so a chance at a different result. the <span t=
itle=3D"Japanese-language text"><i lang=3D"ja-Latn">gacha</i></span>, retur=
ning their drawn item in exchange for another opportunity to draw, so as to=
 potentially get something else. Some games offer this feature for free.<su=
p id=3D"cite_ref-itsconferencepaper_13-1" class=3D"reference"><a href=3D"ht=
tps://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Gacha_game#cite_note-itsconferencepaper-13"><sp=
an class=3D"cite-bracket">[</span>13<span class=3D"cite-bracket">]</span></=
a></sup> Games commonly offer some free rolls at the start, e.g. during a t=
utorial. Players might "re-roll" by creating new accounts and doing the sta=
rter rolls on each until they get the draws they want.<sup id=3D"cite_ref-i=
ndex_15-0" class=3D"reference"><a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Gac=
ha_game#cite_note-index-15"><span class=3D"cite-bracket">[</span>15<span cl=
ass=3D"cite-bracket">]</span></a></sup></dd>
<dt>Consecutive <span title=3D"Japanese-language text"><i lang=3D"ja-Latn">=
gacha</i></span></dt>
<dd>Consecutive <span title=3D"Japanese-language text"><i lang=3D"ja-Latn">=
gacha</i></span> improves the chances of receiving rare rewards when the pl=
ayer spends in bulk. As opposed to spending a set amount for individual rol=
ls, a player can spend a larger amount in order to roll several times in a =
row for a slightly discounted price.<sup id=3D"cite_ref-serkantoto_14-1" cl=
ass=3D"reference"><a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Gacha_game#cite_=
note-serkantoto-14"><span class=3D"cite-bracket">[</span>14<span class=3D"c=
ite-bracket">]</span></a></sup></dd>
<dt>Step-up <span title=3D"Japanese-language text"><i lang=3D"ja-Latn">gach=
a</i></span></dt>
<dd>The player's rates are improved for each consecutive roll or instance o=
f spending within a single session or a limited time period (e.g. five chec=
kpoints; must roll five times or spend five times within half an hour to ge=
t the rewards for step one, two, three, four, and five in succession.)<sup =
id=3D"cite_ref-serkantoto_14-2" class=3D"reference"><a href=3D"https://en.w=
ikipedia.org/wiki/Gacha_game#cite_note-serkantoto-14"><span class=3D"cite-b=
racket">[</span>14<span class=3D"cite-bracket">]</span></a></sup></dd>
<dt>Open versus closed <span title=3D"Japanese-language text"><i lang=3D"ja=
-Latn">gacha</i></span></dt>
<dd><span title=3D"Japanese-language text"><i lang=3D"ja-Latn">Gacha</i></s=
pan> that show (open) versus hide (closed) the exact probabilities of pulli=
ng rare items.<sup id=3D"cite_ref-itsconferencepaper_13-2" class=3D"referen=
ce"><a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Gacha_game#cite_note-itsconfer=
encepaper-13"><span class=3D"cite-bracket">[</span>13<span class=3D"cite-br=
acket">]</span></a></sup></dd></dl>
<div class=3D"mw-heading mw-heading2"><h2 id=3D"Appeal">Appeal</h2><span cl=
ass=3D"mw-editsection"><span class=3D"mw-editsection-bracket">[</span><a hr=
ef=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/w/index.php?title=3DGacha_game&amp;action=3D=
edit&amp;section=3D4" title=3D"Edit section: Appeal"><span>edit</span></a><=
span class=3D"mw-editsection-bracket">]</span></span></div>
<p>Game developers have praised <span title=3D"Japanese-language text"><i l=
ang=3D"ja-Latn">gacha</i></span> as a <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/w=
iki/Free-to-play" title=3D"Free-to-play">free-to-play</a> monetization stra=
tegy.<sup id=3D"cite_ref-willluton_16-0" class=3D"reference"><a href=3D"htt=
ps://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Gacha_game#cite_note-willluton-16"><span class=
=3D"cite-bracket">[</span>16<span class=3D"cite-bracket">]</span></a></sup>=
<sup id=3D"cite_ref-johannesheinze_6-2" class=3D"reference"><a href=3D"http=
s://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Gacha_game#cite_note-johannesheinze-6"><span clas=
s=3D"cite-bracket">[</span>6<span class=3D"cite-bracket">]</span></a></sup>=
 Most developers that work primarily with free-to-play games recommend it b=
e incorporated into the game starting with the concept for maximum monetiza=
tion potential.<sup id=3D"cite_ref-johannesheinze_6-3" class=3D"reference">=
<a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Gacha_game#cite_note-johannesheinz=
e-6"><span class=3D"cite-bracket">[</span>6<span class=3D"cite-bracket">]</=
span></a></sup>
</p><p>It has been debated what makes <span title=3D"Japanese-language text=
"><i lang=3D"ja-Latn">gacha</i></span> so addictive to so many players. Pro=
posed mechanisms include playing on the <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org=
/wiki/Hunter-gatherer" title=3D"Hunter-gatherer">hunter-gatherer</a> instin=
ct to collect items, as well as the desire to complete a set,<sup id=3D"cit=
e_ref-johannesheinze_6-4" class=3D"reference"><a href=3D"https://en.wikiped=
ia.org/wiki/Gacha_game#cite_note-johannesheinze-6"><span class=3D"cite-brac=
ket">[</span>6<span class=3D"cite-bracket">]</span></a></sup> effective use=
 of the <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/FOMO" class=3D"mw-redirect=
" title=3D"FOMO">"fear of missing out"</a>, or, simply the same mechanisms =
that drive <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Gambling" title=3D"Gamb=
ling">gambling</a>.<sup id=3D"cite_ref-willluton_16-1" class=3D"reference">=
<a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Gacha_game#cite_note-willluton-16"=
><span class=3D"cite-bracket">[</span>16<span class=3D"cite-bracket">]</spa=
n></a></sup>
</p><p>The model of <span title=3D"Japanese-language text"><i lang=3D"ja-La=
tn">gacha</i></span> has been compared to that of <a href=3D"https://en.wik=
ipedia.org/wiki/Collectible_trading_card_game" class=3D"mw-redirect" title=
=3D"Collectible trading card game">collectible trading card games</a> as we=
ll as to gambling.<sup id=3D"cite_ref-willluton_16-2" class=3D"reference"><=
a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Gacha_game#cite_note-willluton-16">=
<span class=3D"cite-bracket">[</span>16<span class=3D"cite-bracket">]</span=
></a></sup>
</p><p>An aspect of monetization commonly found in the financing of <i>gach=
a</i> games involves a model where a large part of the game's revenue comes=
 from a very small proportion of players who spend an unusually large amoun=
t of money on <i>gacha</i> rolls, essentially to subsidize the game for oth=
er players who may spend smaller amounts of money, or even <a href=3D"https=
://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Free-to-play" title=3D"Free-to-play">free-to-play<=
/a> players that spend no money at all. The high-spending players are often=
 colloquially referred to as "<a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Whal=
e_(gambling)" class=3D"mw-redirect" title=3D"Whale (gambling)">whales</a>".=
 A player who is called a dolphin spends a moderate amount of money on micr=
otransactions in mobile games. A player who is called a minnow spends littl=
e to no money on microtransactions in mobile games.<sup id=3D"cite_ref-inde=
x_15-1" class=3D"reference"><a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Gacha_=
game#cite_note-index-15"><span class=3D"cite-bracket">[</span>15<span class=
=3D"cite-bracket">]</span></a></sup><sup id=3D"cite_ref-17" class=3D"refere=
nce"><a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Gacha_game#cite_note-17"><spa=
n class=3D"cite-bracket">[</span>17<span class=3D"cite-bracket">]</span></a=
></sup>
</p>
<div class=3D"mw-heading mw-heading2"><h2 id=3D"Gambling-like_mechanics_and=
_regulation">Gambling-like mechanics and regulation</h2><span class=3D"mw-e=
ditsection"><span class=3D"mw-editsection-bracket">[</span><a href=3D"https=
://en.wikipedia.org/w/index.php?title=3DGacha_game&amp;action=3Dedit&amp;se=
ction=3D5" title=3D"Edit section: Gambling-like mechanics and regulation"><=
span>edit</span></a><span class=3D"mw-editsection-bracket">]</span></span><=
/div>
<p>Gacha games have faced significant criticism for their resemblance to ga=
mbling, largely due to their reliance on chance-based mechanics to acquire =
desirable in-game items. Studies in Europe and the United States indicate t=
hat a substantial portion of young players who engage in gacha games develo=
p gambling-like behaviors. For instance, research has shown that over 50% o=
f juveniles who participate in gacha games exhibit some gambling tendencies=
, with around 5% developing problematic habits and 10% showing early signs =
of gambling addiction.<sup id=3D"cite_ref-:3_8-3" class=3D"reference"><a hr=
ef=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Gacha_game#cite_note-:3-8"><span class=
=3D"cite-bracket">[</span>8<span class=3D"cite-bracket">]</span></a></sup><=
sup id=3D"cite_ref-18" class=3D"reference"><a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.=
org/wiki/Gacha_game#cite_note-18"><span class=3D"cite-bracket">[</span>18<s=
pan class=3D"cite-bracket">]</span></a></sup>
</p><p>Some researchers and policymakers argue that gacha monetization syst=
ems may take advantage of players who are susceptible to addictive behavior=
s. <sup id=3D"cite_ref-:3_8-4" class=3D"reference"><a href=3D"https://en.wi=
kipedia.org/wiki/Gacha_game#cite_note-:3-8"><span class=3D"cite-bracket">[<=
/span>8<span class=3D"cite-bracket">]</span></a></sup> The European Union P=
arliament has taken steps to regulate gacha mechanics to protect consumers,=
 citing the exploitative nature of these games.<sup id=3D"cite_ref-19" clas=
s=3D"reference"><a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Gacha_game#cite_no=
te-19"><span class=3D"cite-bracket">[</span>19<span class=3D"cite-bracket">=
]</span></a></sup> Some countries like China require companies to disclose =
the probabilities of obtaining specific items.<sup id=3D"cite_ref-20" class=
=3D"reference"><a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Gacha_game#cite_not=
e-20"><span class=3D"cite-bracket">[</span>20<span class=3D"cite-bracket">]=
</span></a></sup>
</p><p>Studies suggest that players with existing gambling problems are mor=
e likely to spend large amounts of money on gacha systems. Researchers have=
 also noted that the absence of spending limits in many gacha systems may c=
ontribute to higher spending among at-risk players. Some studies estimate t=
hat a significant share of revenue from gacha and loot box systems comes fr=
om players categorized as being at moderate to high risk for gambling-relat=
ed harm.<sup id=3D"cite_ref-21" class=3D"reference"><a href=3D"https://en.w=
ikipedia.org/wiki/Gacha_game#cite_note-21"><span class=3D"cite-bracket">[</=
span>21<span class=3D"cite-bracket">]</span></a></sup>
</p><p>Legal classification varies by jurisdiction. Some regulators do not =
consider gacha mechanics to be gambling. For example, the UK's legal framew=
ork does not classify gacha as gambling since the virtual items obtained do=
 not have real-world monetary value.<sup id=3D"cite_ref-22" class=3D"refere=
nce"><a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Gacha_game#cite_note-22"><spa=
n class=3D"cite-bracket">[</span>22<span class=3D"cite-bracket">]</span></a=
></sup> However, the Netherlands Gambling Authority and the Belgium Gaming =
Commission view gacha as gambling due to its reliance on chance and the pot=
ential for items to be traded for real money on third-party sites.<sup id=
=3D"cite_ref-23" class=3D"reference"><a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wi=
ki/Gacha_game#cite_note-23"><span class=3D"cite-bracket">[</span>23<span cl=
ass=3D"cite-bracket">]</span></a></sup>
</p><p>Research has linked the appeal of gacha mechanics to psychological r=
esponses associated with randomness, reward anticipation, and variable-rati=
o reinforcement. Studies comparing gacha systems to gambling note that the =
anticipation of obtaining rare items can produce responses similar to those=
 observed in traditional gambling contexts.<sup id=3D"cite_ref-24" class=3D=
"reference"><a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Gacha_game#cite_note-2=
4"><span class=3D"cite-bracket">[</span>24<span class=3D"cite-bracket">]</s=
pan></a></sup> Some gacha implementations have been described as "pay-to-wi=
n" by players and critics, while others offer optional purchases that do no=
t substantially affect progression. The impact on players largely depends o=
n how the developers implement the gacha mechanics and whether they are ess=
ential for game progression or merely provide optional enhancements.<sup id=
=3D"cite_ref-25" class=3D"reference"><a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wi=
ki/Gacha_game#cite_note-25"><span class=3D"cite-bracket">[</span>25<span cl=
ass=3D"cite-bracket">]</span></a></sup>
</p><p>In response to growing concerns, some jurisdictions have implemented=
 regulations requiring transparency in drop rates and banning particularly =
exploitative practices. Gacha systems remain a widely used and commercially=
 successful monetization model in mobile games.<sup id=3D"cite_ref-26" clas=
s=3D"reference"><a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Gacha_game#cite_no=
te-26"><span class=3D"cite-bracket">[</span>26<span class=3D"cite-bracket">=
]</span></a></sup><sup id=3D"cite_ref-27" class=3D"reference"><a href=3D"ht=
tps://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Gacha_game#cite_note-27"><span class=3D"cite-br=
acket">[</span>27<span class=3D"cite-bracket">]</span></a></sup><sup id=3D"=
cite_ref-28" class=3D"reference"><a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/G=
acha_game#cite_note-28"><span class=3D"cite-bracket">[</span>28<span class=
=3D"cite-bracket">]</span></a></sup><sup id=3D"cite_ref-29" class=3D"refere=
nce"><a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Gacha_game#cite_note-29"><spa=
n class=3D"cite-bracket">[</span>29<span class=3D"cite-bracket">]</span></a=
></sup><sup id=3D"cite_ref-:2_30-0" class=3D"reference"><a href=3D"https://=
en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Gacha_game#cite_note-:2-30"><span class=3D"cite-brack=
et">[</span>30<span class=3D"cite-bracket">]</span></a></sup>
</p>
